$var = $abilities ?? ['foo', 'bar', 'bar'] ?? [

title: Spaces get condensed by --fix when they are alone in a <span>
body: We often need to add spacing between two elements in JSX. For example: ```jsx {' '} ``` Applying `--fix` turns the code into this: ```jsx ``` which is not the same thing. I think I've traced down what's happening. The code above gives off this error: ``` error Curly braces are unnecessary here react/jsx-curly-brace-presence ``` Which, when corrected (by removing the curly braces and quotes), gives off another error: ``` error Empty components are self-closing react/self-closing-comp ``` which `--fix` happily turns into the `` above. Versions: * `eslint@4.18.2` * `eslint-plugin-react@7.7.0`

title: PNG with long iTXt chunk not detected as PNG image
Istanbul throws when pitching loader is used
body:
When using a pitching loader such as:
https://github.com/walmartlabs/circus-handlebars#programatically-loading-modules
https://github.com/walmartlabs/circus-handlebars/blob/master/lib/loaders/helper.js

Istanbul fails to report coverage properly due to `resourcePath` having the same value for both the original request, `require('helper!foo')`, and the request made by the pitching loader, `require('!foo')`.

I could not find a way to generically prevent the coverage tool from running on the code emitted by the pitching loader and had to use `require('!!helper!foo')` to fix the coverage reporting.

title: Using autoload with cash-dom and vue causes "$ is not a function"

    Before posting this issue, please perform the following steps, and confirm that the issue is still present.

1. Update Laravel Mix to the latest version. (`npm update laravel-mix` or `yarn upgrade laravel-mix --latest`)
2. Nuke your dependencies, and reinstall from scratch: `rm -rf node_modules && npm cache clear && npm install`.

-   Laravel Mix Version: 4.0.16

title: Memory leak detected
body:
Preliminary note. I didn't installed inflight directly, it's just a package that [glob](https://github.com/isaacs/node-glob) uses.

```
$ npm list inflight
myLibrary@0.0.1 path/to/myLibrary
`-- glob@7.1.2
  `-- inflight@1.0.6
```

I'm developing a CLI apps that scans a set of files in the user's disk. Sometimes, it stops working throwing the following log:

```
<--- Last few GCs --->

[7828:000001CAE9906BF0]      729 ms: Mark-sweep 27.1 (94.3) -> [...] allocation failure GC in old space requested
[7828:000001CAE9906BF0]      754 ms: Mark-sweep 27.1 (94.3) -> [...]  last resort
[7828:000001CAE9906BF0]      780 ms: Mark-sweep 27.1 (32.3) -> [...] last resort


<--- JS stacktrace --->

==== JS stack trace =========================================

Security context: 000002CEAE928799 <JSObject>
    1: _readdirEntries [path\to\myLibrary\node_modules\glob\glob.js:~559] [pc=000002F43C32198C](this=0000001978260B49 <Glob map = 000000777A7EB871>,abs=0000027C3514ED71 [...]

FATAL ERROR: CALL_AND_RETRY_LAST Allocation failed - JavaScript heap out of memory
```

So, I've inspected the Node's process' heap usage (node --inspect myLibrary.js) and got the following result, in which the **inflight** module is the most expensive package in terms of retained size.

![memory leak](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12381818/33765635-19da6882-dc1a-11e7-9b9a-48e9dc44441c.JPG)

title: Typescript with commonjs module loader
body: - Laravel Mix Version: 1.4.2 - Node Version: 8.4.0 - Yarn Version: 1.0.1 - OS: OSx Sierra ### Description: ``` // tsconfig.json { "compileOnSave": false, "compilerOptions": { "target": "ES5", "module": "commonjs", "lib": [ "dom", "es2017" ], "types": [ "node" ], "moduleResolution": "node", "allowSyntheticDefaultImports": true, "emitDecoratorMetadata": true, "experimentalDecorators": true, "removeComments": true, "noImplicitAny": true, "sourceMap": true, "outDir": "build/" }, "exclude": [ "node_modules" ] } ``` (Note the `allowSyntheticDefaultImports` settings is enabled as recommended by Vue) ```typescript // app.ts import Vue from "vue" console.dir(Vue) const app = new Vue({ el: "#app", template: ` Hello World! ` }) ``` It should be possible to use `commonjs` as module loader for Typescript. However, running `mix.ts()` breaks this somehow, as the result in the browser is the following. `console.dir(): undefined` With the following error: ``` app.js:83 Uncaught TypeError: vue_1.Vue is not a constructor at Object._toString (app.js:83) at __webpack_require__ (app.js:20) at Object.defineProperty.value (app.js:70) at __webpack_require__ (app.js:20) at app.js:63 at app.js:66 ``` I've tried setting up a webpack configuration for typescript and run it on the same `app.ts` file with the same `tsconfig.json` (and aswell with `ts-loader` as used in laravel-mix). ```javascript // webpack.config.js module.exports = { entry: "./app.ts", output: { filename: "app.js", path: __dirname + "/dist" }, devtool: "source-map", resolve: { extensions: [".ts", ".tsx", ".js", ".json", ".vue"], alias: { 'vue$': 'vue/dist/vue.esm.js' } }, module: { rules: [ { test: /\.tsx?$/, loader: "ts-loader" }, { enforce: "pre", test: /\.js$/, loader: "source-map-loader" } ] } }; ``` That way it works like a charm without any errors. This seems to be a problem in laravel mix. ### Steps To Reproduce: 0. Add the snippet of `app.ts` 1. Create the `tsconfig.json` above. 2. run `mix.ts()` on `app.ts` 3. Include the generated js and visit the site
Comments: Is an issue with Laravel Mix not Vue

title: Incompatible with ReadableStream from node@6.3.0
body:
Since https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/7077 was merged and released in node@6.3.0 the internal `buffer` of a readable stream is no longer an array but a `BufferList`. Due to this issue tests started breaking with that release with the following error:

```
TypeError: Cannot read property 'length' of undefined
    at Connection.Duplexify._forward (/home/travis/build/ipfs/js-ipfs/node_modules/interface-connection/node_modules/duplexify/index.js:170:76)
    at Duplex.onreadable (/home/travis/build/ipfs/js-ipfs/node_modules/interface-connection/node_modules/duplexify/index.js:127:10)
    at emitNone (events.js:86:13)
    at Duplex.emit (events.js:185:7)
    at emitReadable_ (_stream_readable.js:433:10)
    at emitReadable (_stream_readable.js:427:7)
    at readableAddChunk (_stream_readable.js:188:13)
    at Duplex.Readable.push (_stream_readable.js:135:10)
```
Comments: Node merge caused buffers to change from array to a buffer list breaking downstream project

title: Generator definition shorthand outputs as function
body:
<!-- Please don't delete this template because we'll close your issue -->
<!-- Before creating an issue please make sure you are using the latest version of webpack. -->

# Bug report

<!-- Please ask questions on StackOverflow or the webpack Gitter. -->
<!-- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/ask?tags=webpack -->
<!-- https://gitter.im/webpack/webpack -->
<!-- Issues which contain questions or support requests will be closed. -->

**What is the current behavior?**

The [shorthand for defining a generator method in an object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/Method_definitions) is sometimes parsed as a function. In some cases, this raises an uncaught syntax error in the browser (because keywords such as `yield`, `yield*` cannot be used in functions), causing the site to fail in executing the bundled js file.

**If the current behavior is a bug, please provide the steps to reproduce.**

Input `src/index.js`:

```javascript
export const foo = {
  *bar() { return yield 'something' }
}
```

Output `dist/main.js`:

```javascript
...const n={bar:()=>yield"something"}}]);
```

<!-- A great way to do this is to provide your configuration via a GitHub repository -->
<!-- The most helpful is a minimal reproduction with instructions on how to reproduce -->
<!-- Repositories with too many files or large `webpack.config.js` files are not suitable -->
<!-- Please only add small code snippets directly into this issue -->
<!-- https://gist.github.com is a good place for longer code snippets -->
<!-- If your issue is caused by a plugin or loader, please create an issue on the loader/plugin repository instead -->

**What is the expected behavior?**

The output should be,

```javascript
...const n={*bar(){return yield"something"}}}]);
```

<!-- "It should work" is not a helpful explanation -->
<!-- Explain exactly how it should behave -->

**Other relevant information:**
webpack version:  4.12.0
Node.js version: v9.11.1
Operating System: Debian 9.4 stretch
Additional tools: -


---

This issue was moved from webpack/webpack#7566 by @sokra. Original issue was by @ningyuansg.
Comments: Seems like an issue within the webpack package

title: SSR cannot generate preload scripts of assets (by ssrContext.renderResourceHints()
body:
### Version
14.2.1

### Reproduction link
[https://github.com/nuxt/nuxt.js/blob/feat/webpack4/test/with-config.test.js#L46-L53](https://github.com/nuxt/nuxt.js/blob/feat/webpack4/test/with-config.test.js#L46-L53)

### Steps to reproduce
Try to get preload scripts of assets in SSR resources hints by calling `ssrContext.renderResourceHints()`


### What is expected?
Preload scripts of assets can generate successfully

### What is actually happening?
Preload scripts of assets are empty

---
Currently we are working on the [upgrading to Webpack4 in Nuxt](https://github.com/nuxt/nuxt.js/pull/2901), we met this issue in SSR font-preloading.

After some investigations, I found the issue was caused by two reasons.

1. Webpack module assets is null, I have opened a pr https://github.com/webpack/webpack/pull/6640 (**merged**)
2. Webpack ConcatenatedModule has changed module identifier to `request   additional hash`, but `vue-loader` is still using `request`.

    * [`ConcatenatedModule identifier`](https://github.com/webpack/webpack/blob/master/lib/optimize/ConcatenatedModule.js#L434)

    * [`SSR plugin is using identifier which has been modified by ConcatenatedModule`](https://github.com/vuejs/vue/blob/dev/src/server/webpack-plugin/client.js#L46)

    * [`vue-loader is using request`](https://github.com/vuejs/vue-loader/blob/master/lib/loader.js#L250)

I'm not very sure the fix should be done in vue-ssr or vue-loader, so just opened issue here, we can have a discussion and figure out the solution üò∏

title: Suggested improvement for Vim+ALE integration
body:
**Environments:**
- Prettier Version: 1.15.2
- Running Prettier via: neovim+ALE
- Runtime: Node 10.12.0
- Operating System: GNU/Linux

**Steps to reproduce:**
:wave: hello there, I'm a neovim+ALE user, and after following the steps in [the documentation](https://prettier.io/docs/en/vim.html#ale-https-githubcom-w0rp-ale) I was unable to make *prettier* working for my setup.

TL;DR, I've added those lines to my `$MYVIMRC`:

```
Plug 'w0rp/ale'

let g:ale_fixers = {
\   'javascript': ['prettier'],
\   'css': ['prettier'],
\}

let g:ale_fix_on_save = 1
```

**Expected behavior:**
The expected behavior was to have ALE running prettier, and format the file on save.

**Actual behavior:**
[Standard](https://github.com/standard/standard) was running instead :confused:.

**Possible solution:**
After digging a bit, I found this in the [ALE FAQ](https://github.com/w0rp/ale#5i-how-do-i-disable-particular-linters):

> By default, all available tools for all supported languages will be run. If you want to only select a subset of the tools, you can define `b:ale_linters` for a single buffer, or `g:ale_linters globally`.
[...]
If you don't want ALE to run anything other than what you've explicitly asked for, you can set `g:ale_linters_explicit` to 1.

By adding `let g:ale_linters_explicit = 1` to my `$MYVIMRC` I was finally able to use *prettier* :tada:.

If that's the correct approach, I can make a PR to update the documentation, what do you think?

title: Using `module` for `hot` cancels some webpack optimizations in prod
body:
```js import React from 'react' import { hot } from 'react-hot-loader' const App = () =>
Hello World!
export default hot(module)(App) ``` This code uses `module` variable. This cancels at least [concatenateModules](https://webpack.js.org/configuration/optimization/#optimization-concatenatemodules) optimization (enabled in prod mode) https://github.com/webpack/webpack/blob/af90df9998c2aec0a9f8fbb6c488a0c423b1a331/lib/optimize/ModuleConcatenationPlugin.js#L104 Seems like bundles that using RHL has the worst size and eval-performance because some webpack-optimizations just not applying I've created a simple babel-plugin, that replaces `export default hot(module)(App)` by `export default App` and it dropped **200kb** from total bundle size by dropping useless code and by ModuleConcatenationPlugin stuff. Not—É that we have only 8 places where we using `hot` in our code. 200kb for only 8 places... not bad... But it seems like a hack... I think, that the problem should be solved on RHL side. I can create a PR to `babel.prod.js` with replacing `hot(module)(App)` by `App`
Potential Reclassification: possibly an optimization problem rather than an intrinsic bug.

Unnecessary "Unexpected key ..." warning when merging combined reducers
body:
**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**  

A bug... maybe.  It seems like it's intended behaviour but I don't know who benefits from the warning.

It is similar to #1636, but not caused by `replaceReducers`, but by wanting to merge the state from seperate reducers, which have been combined with `combineReducers`.

**What is the current behavior?**

When `combineReducers` receives keys it doesn't know about it produces a warning stating

> Unexpected key "additional" found in previous state received by the reducer. Expected to find one of the known reducer keys instead: "known". Unexpected keys will be ignored.

**If the current behavior is a bug, please provide the steps to reproduce and if possible a minimal demo of the problem via https://jsfiddle.net or similar.**

[Here is a codepen](https://codepen.io/anon/pen/xdNgPB) with a simplified example of what I'm doing.

**What is the expected behavior?**

I would not expect to see this warning, as I believe that merging state from multiple reducers is a valid use case for Redux.  Even one of the [examples in the Redux docs](http://redux.js.org/docs/recipes/reducers/BeyondCombineReducers.html#sharing-data-between-slice-reducers) would have the same issue if the `crossSliceReducer` added a new key rather than overriding an existing one.

I don't really understand who is benefitting from this warning.  If it was warning about a missing key (after it has previously been there and there was a slice reducer expecting it) I would understand that that is something that is unusual and probably a bug, but I don't see much harm in having additional nodes that the reducer is just going to ignore anyway.

**Which versions of Redux, and which browser and OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of Redux?**

I am unsure which version of Redux introduced the warning and why, but it is still present in 3.6.0

title: got.stream creating different file from same URL
body:
This is a weird one...

I wrote this script `fuckyou.js`:
```
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');
const got = require('got');

got.stream('https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/scl-cdn/doomtrooper/assets/video.md5').pipe(fs.createWriteStream(path.join(__dirname, '/fuckyou.md5')));
```

And then I run it...

```
‚ûú  dt-client git:(master) ‚úó node fuckyou.js 
‚ûú  dt-client git:(master) ‚úó cat fuckyou.md5 
b05eea1123e1b191dc4aa198ec62422f
```

But inside my electron code, I put:

```
got.stream('https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/scl-cdn/doomtrooper/assets/video.md5').pipe(fs.createWriteStream(path.join(__dirname, '/fuckyou.md5')));
```

which creates the `fuckyou.md5` in my electron folder...

contents:
```
61bf54985c111c3bb43cace3ceb655ea

title: Bug: Code coverage thresholds not respected
body:
Please use the template provided below, when reporting bugs:
-----

## Expected Behavior
Programmatic use of NYC with breached code coverage thresholds results in a non-zero exit code.

## Observed Behavior
While using NYC programmatically (via the `.wrap()` interface), coverage threshold breaches result in an exit code of `0`.

## Bonus Points! Code (or Repository) that Reproduces Issue
https://github.com/kunagpal/express-boilerplate/blob/develop/scripts/test/run.js#L104

## Related issues and pull requests:
https://github.com/istanbuljs/nyc/issues/384 [This one reports issues for Node v0.10]
https://github.com/istanbuljs/nyc/pull/386 [This P.R fixes the above bug]

## Suggestion
I feel the code here: https://github.com/istanbuljs/nyc/blob/master/index.js#L459 can be changed to the following:
```js
process.exitCode && process.exit(process.exitCode); // ensures that code coverage is enforced correctly
```
The existing check on process.version will result in the exit code constraint being satisfied for Node `v0.10.x` - `0.11.x` only.

## Forensic Information

**Operating System:** MacOSX Sierra.
**Environment Information:** information about your project's environment, see instructions below:

1. run the following script:

sh -c 'node --version; npm --version; npm ls' > output.txt

2. share a gist with the contents of output.txt.
https://gist.github.com/kunagpal/3f7f7d9c16fddaa8909797c06fec2bc0

PS: I'll be more than happy to send a P.R that fixes this issue.
Potential Reclassification: I think this is non-bug, the contributor closed it and says this isnt an issue with NYC.

title: Unescape `Identifier` is not safe
body:
Case 1:

```js
for (async of []); // invalid
for (\u0061sync of []); // valid
for ((async) of []); // Prettier output
```

We add `()` to `async` as a workaround. Example copied from [here](https://github.com/estree/estree/issues/291#issuecomment-1296273529)

Case 2:

```js
for (using of of of); // Invalid
for (using o\u0066 of of); // Valid
```

I do know how to fix this. "Explicit Resource Management" support PR https://github.com/prettier/prettier/pull/13752

title: Standard should also check files that are in .gitignore but added to git
body:
### Steps to reproduce

1. Create a file that violates standardjs rules: `invalid.js`
2. Add `invalid.js` (or `*`, `invalid.*`, etc.) to `.gitignore`
3. Run `git add -f invalid.js` and `git commit`
4. Run `standard`

### Expected behaviour

`standard` should print error messages for `invalid.js`

### Current behaviour

`standard` ignores `invalid.js`

title: mapSources behave different in Linux with node v6.9.2 and Windows with node  v7.7.1
createStore should perhaps accept preloadedState: PreloadedState<S> | S
body: At least as of `4.0.5`, `createStore` accepts `preloadedState: PreloadedState<S>`. One imagines that one can pass `S` to `preloadedState`, and in most cases this is correct. However, there are cases in which `S` is not assignable to `PreloadedState<S>`, at least since `typescript@3.6.3`. See https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/35992 for more information on this issue. It's unclear to me whether https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/35992 is a typescript bug, but I'm wondering if `createStore` should accept `preloadedState: PreloadedState<S> | S`, which would mitigate the issue of branded types being mapped to `never`.

title: Running manifest causes emits otherwise unmodified files
Inconsistency breaking assignments
body:
For example,

```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes = 
  anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes;
```

[formats as](https://prettier.io/playground/#%7B%22content%22%3A%22aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%20%5Cn%20%20anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes%3B%5Cn%22%2C%22options%22%3A%7B%22printWidth%22%3A80%2C%22tabWidth%22%3A2%2C%22singleQuote%22%3Afalse%2C%22trailingComma%22%3A%22none%22%2C%22bracketSpacing%22%3Atrue%2C%22jsxBracketSameLine%22%3Afalse%2C%22parser%22%3A%22babylon%22%2C%22semi%22%3Atrue%2C%22useTabs%22%3Afalse%2C%22doc%22%3Afalse%2C%22ast%22%3Afalse%7D%7D)

```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes = anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes;
```

Similarly there is no break after the `=` in

```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes =
  'a very long string for illustrative purposes'.length;
```
or
```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes =
  anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes();
```
although there *is* in
```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes =
  anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes.length;
```
and
```js
aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes =
  anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes + 1;
```

I'd expect every one of these to break after the `=`, since otherwise line length exceeds 80 characters. (Though I thought it used to... is this an intentional, or a regression?)

[Here's a link](https://prettier.io/playground/#%7B%22content%22%3A%22aParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%20%5Cn%20%20anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes%3B%5Cn%5CnaParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%5Cn%20%20'a%20very%20long%20string%20for%20illustrative%20purposes'.length%3B%5Cn%5CnaParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%5Cn%20%20anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes.length%3B%5Cn%5CnaParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%5Cn%20%20anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes()%3B%5Cn%5CnaParticularlyLongAndObnoxiousNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%3D%5Cn%20%20anotherVeryLongNameForIllustrativePurposes%20%2B%201%3B%5Cn%22%2C%22options%22%3A%7B%22printWidth%22%3A80%2C%22tabWidth%22%3A2%2C%22singleQuote%22%3Afalse%2C%22trailingComma%22%3A%22none%22%2C%22bracketSpacing%22%3Atrue%2C%22jsxBracketSameLine%22%3Afalse%2C%22parser%22%3A%22babylon%22%2C%22semi%22%3Atrue%2C%22useTabs%22%3Afalse%2C%22doc%22%3Afalse%2C%22ast%22%3Afalse%7D%7D) containing all of these cases.

This also applies to variable declarations.

title: Skips styles
[react/jsx-filename-extension] Restrict .js extension
body:
This is regarding the rule: 
https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/blob/master/docs/rules/jsx-filename-extension.md

There are a few comments I read that convinced me to use `.js` extensions for my react components (that contains jsx) including 
1. [Dan abramov's comment here](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/pull/985#issuecomment-239145468).
2. Also the create-react-app project now encourages `.js` extension for react components.

So If I'm going ahead with this, I wanted to enforce this for our codebase because our tooling will no longer read `jsx` files anymore.

Taking this from the documentation:
```
"react/jsx-filename-extension": [1, { "extensions": [".js", ".jsx"] }]
```
I though, maybe if I modify the `extensions` array to be just `".js"` it might work.
```
"react/jsx-filename-extension": [1, { "extensions": [".js"] }]
```

but it didn't. What could be the reason for that ?

Since this is a pretty generic rule that says in it's documentation:
> Restrict file extensions that may contain JSX

I think this use case is something that could belong here.

title: btoa should throw InvalidCharacterError for out of range character
body: Per [spec](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/webappapis.html#atob:dom-windowbase64-btoa-3) it should throw `InvalidCharacterError` instead of returning `null`. Although browsers are not consistent about type of error they throw, they always throw an error.

title: Confusing reformatting of multiline function arguments with functions in them
body:
Sorry about the title, I found out it's not so easy for me to describe the problem ;)

I encountered the problem using [reselect](https://github.com/reactjs/reselect)'s createSelector, but this applies to many use cases, in particular when using React/Redux and HoCs.

Original code:
```js
const selectRedirectionQuery = () => createSelector(
  selectRoute(),
  (routingState) => routingState.getIn(['locationBeforeTransitions', 'query', 'redirect'])
);
```

Output (options: ` --trailing-comma=true --bracket-spacing=true --single-quote=true`):
```js
const selectRedirectionQuery = () =>
  createSelector(selectRoute(), routingState =>
    routingState.getIn(['locationBeforeTransitions', 'query', 'redirect']));
```

Expected one of these, depending on the closure's length:
```js
const selectRedirectionQuery = () =>
  createSelector(
    selectRoute(),
    routingState =>
      routingState.getIn(['locationBeforeTransitions', 'query', 'redirect'])
  );
```
```js
const selectRedirectionQuery = () =>
  createSelector(
    selectRoute(),
    routingState => routingState.getIn(['locationBeforeTransitions', 'query', 'redirect'])
  );
```

The current output seems to me to be really hard to parse correctly.

title: SassError: Invalid CSS after " ": expected 1 selector or at-rule, was "{"
body:
### Version
16.0.0-beta.4

### Reproduction link
[https://github.com](https://github.com)







### Steps to reproduce
`vue create site`
choose vue3 and sass
change App.vue style like this:

```
<style lang="sass">
    #app
        font-family: Avenir, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif
        -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased
        -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale
        text-align: center
        color: #007dff
        margin-top: 60px
</style>
```

make sure that `#App` has 4 space indent.

npm run serve, error.

### What is expected?
serve

### What is actually happening?
abrupt

---
this is an available work around: add a line in `node_modules/sass-loader/dist/index.js`:

```
function loader(content) {
    const options = (0, _loaderUtils.getOptions)(this);
```

to 

```
function loader(content) {
    content = content.replace(/^[ \r\n]*/, '')
    const options = (0, _loaderUtils.getOptions)(this);
```

title: [Bug] thisCompilation.mainTemplate is never hit
"Invalid descriptor for property 'dispatch'" in IE11
body:
**Do you want to request a _feature_ or report a _bug_?**

Bug.

**What is the current behavior?**

With Redux 4.0.2 and up, IE11 throws up an error on load of "Invalid descriptor for property 'dispatch'." The script debugger flags 570,9 in redux.js as the source of the error (which appears to be inside the _objectSpread2(target) function. I don't think this is the source of the error itself as that function exists within previous versions of Redux and seems unchanged between versions. Redux 4.0.1 works fine and does not have this issue.

**What is the expected behavior?**

Redux works normally as expected.

**Which versions of Redux, and which browser and OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of Redux?**

4.0.2 and 4.0.3 running in IE11 on Windows 10. No other browser seems to be affected. Previous versions (4.0.1 being the most recent) worked.

title: HTML Parser not not support quotes in interpolated attributes
body:
In certain situations with template interpolation, quotes inside an HTML attribute could be valid HTML. The current HTML parser throws an exception when an interpolation attribute contains a quote. **Prettier pr-5800** [Playground link](https://deploy-preview-5800--prettier.netlify.com/playground/#) ```sh --parser lwc ``` **Input:** ```html
``` **Output:** ```html SyntaxError: Unexpected closing tag "div". It may happen when the tag has already been closed by another tag. For more info see https://www.w3.org/TR/html5/syntax.html#closing-elements-that-have-implied-end-tags (1:54) > 1 |
| ^ ``` **Expected behavior:** The HTML parser should parse these values correctly so they can be used in the interpolation value.

I have a lerna repo using npm's relatively new "file:" dependency feature to load resources from parent directories. For a given package when I run "npm run test" within a package it should use nyc/mocha from ../../node_modules/.bin.

If I install nyc globally (wish to avoid) and run directly (without ../../node_modules/.bin/nyc) **files are be covered correctly**. However when running as above only one file will show coverage.

### How Do We Reproduce?

<!--
  Issues without minimal reproductions will be closed! Please provide one by:
  1. Using the REPL at https://rollupjs.org/repl, or
  2. Work to isolate the problem and provide the exact steps in this issue, or
  3. Provide a minimal repository link (Read https://git.io/fNzHA for instructions).
     These may take more time to triage than the other options.
-->
Create a simple plugin which uses the `generateBundle` hook to read output file:

```js
const fs = require('fs')

module.exports = () => ({
  generateBundle({ file }, _, isWrite) {
    if (isWrite) {
      fs.readFileSync(file) // Error because it does not exist yet!
    }
  }
})
```

This should be a bug since `onwrite` hook works as expected but it's deprecated in favor of this.


### Expected Behavior

Should be able to access output files when `isWrite` is `true`.


### Actual Behavior

No output files.

It seems `generateBundle` hook is always executed in the `generate` function:

https://github.com/rollup/rollup/blob/4f192335f2cac82897c457ac6cd0d524036ccd5b/src/rollup/index.ts#L293

while `writeOutputFile` is called after that:

https://github.com/rollup/rollup/blob/4f192335f2cac82897c457ac6cd0d524036ccd5b/src/rollup/index.ts#L320

Okay ([sandbox](https://rollupjs.org/repl/?version=2.7.6&))

Not okay: ([sandbox](https://rollupjs.org/repl/?version=2.7.6&))

### Expected Behavior

Bundle works the same as unbundled code.

### Actual Behavior

```
SyntaxError: expected expression, got '}'
```

<!--
  Most issues can be expressed or demonstrated through the REPL or a repository.
  However, the situation may arise where some small code snippets also need to
  be provided. In that situation, please add your code below using
  Fenced Code Blocks (https://help.github.com/articles/creating-and-highlighting-code-blocks/)
-->

The repro case is short, so I will provide it here for reference:

This works as expected:
```js
console.log({        
	test: x =>
		x === "foo"
			? {
				assert: [],
			}
	: {},
})
```

But if I add `true || ` to the condition, Rollup recognizes that it's always true and removes the ternary.  This is fine, except that it leaves the trailing comma (on a separate line), which is a syntax error:

Result with `true || `:

```js
define(function () { 'use strict';

	console.log({        
		test: x =>
			 {
					assert: [],
				}
		,
	});
});
```

Note that if I collapse the `assert` object onto a single line, the resulting code is also okay.

title: "no-unused-prop-types" False Positive When Prop Used in "getDerivedStateFromProps" React 16 Lifecyle Method.
Unhandled promise rejection with "socket hang up" & timeout
body:
On `socket hang up` errors, [timeouts are not cleared](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got/blob/master/source/utils/timed-out.ts#L74).
When the `socket hang up` occurs, it is immediately thrown so the promise returned by got immediately rejects. But as timeouts are not cleared, you will get an unhandled promise rejection after the time set in your timeout.

 - Node.js version: 13.2.0
 - OS & version: Ubuntu 19.10

#### Actual behavior

```
UnhandledPromiseRejectionWarning: GotError: Timeout awaiting 'request' for 1000ms
    at onError (/home/clement/dev/tests/node_modules/got/dist/source/request-as-event-emitter.js:121:29)
    at ClientRequest.<anonymous> (/home/clement/dev/tests/node_modules/got/dist/source/request-as-event-emitter.js:136:21)
    at Object.onceWrapper (events.js:300:26)
    at ClientRequest.emit (events.js:215:7)
    at Immediate.timeoutHandler [as _onImmediate] (/home/clement/dev/tests/node_modules/got/dist/source/utils/timed-out.js:58:17)
    at Immediate.timeoutHandler [as _onImmediate] (/home/clement/dev/tests/node_modules/got/dist/source/utils/timed-out.js:58:31)
    at processImmediate (internal/timers.js:441:21)
    at emitUnhandledRejectionWarning (internal/process/promises.js:141:15)
    at processPromiseRejections (internal/process/promises.js:203:11)
    at processTicksAndRejections (internal/process/task_queues.js:94:32)
```

#### Code to reproduce

You need a `socket hang up` to see the bug. A good manner to have one if to put `socket.destroy();` [here](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got/blob/master/source/utils/timed-out.ts#L108). It's a simulation, but I can generate the same stack trace as my real life application where "true" `socket hang up`s sometimes occur.
```js
'use strict';

const got = require('got');

const gotOptions = {
	timeout: 1000,
	retry: 0
};
got('https://google.com', gotOptions)
	.catch((e) => {
		console.log(e.message)
	});

setTimeout(() => {}, 5000);
```

#### Checklist

- [x] I have read the documentation.
- [x] I have tried my code with the latest version of Node.js and Got.

3. Check your `package.json` file, and ensure that there are no old Laravel Elixir dependencies that might be interfering with Mix.
-->

- Laravel Mix Version: 1.6.1
- Node Version: 8.9.1
- NPM Version: 5.5.1
- OS: macOS 10.13.1

### Description:
Calling `mix.sourceMaps(true, 'source-map')` will not cause `source-map` to be set as the preferred type when building for production. Instead, `cheap-source-map` will be used. Furthermore, no source maps are emitted for javascript bundles in production builds regardless; they are only emitted for bundled css.

I modified [the sourceMaps method in Api.js](https://github.com/JeffreyWay/laravel-mix/blob/master/src/Api.js#L377-L385) as follows to force my own map type preference to be honored during both production and development builds, but javascript source maps are still not emitted.

```javascript
   sourceMaps(productionToo = true, type) {
        if (Mix.inProduction() && !productionToo) {
            // No production source maps!
            type = false;
        }  else if (Mix.inProduction() && typeof type === 'undefined') {
            // Unspecified type preference, fall back to the prod default.
            type = 'cheap-source-map';
        } else if (typeof type === 'undefined') {
            // Not in prod, and no type preference. Fall back to the dev default.
            type = 'inline-source-map';
        }

        Config.sourcemaps = type;

        return this;
    };
```

I plan to continue investigating this issue myself, since I need full sourcemaps for prod builds to send to Bugsnag. But any advice would be greatly appreciated.

### Steps To Reproduce:

<!-- 

Your issue will be addressed much more quickly if you can provide us exact steps to reproduce the problem from scratch.

-->

Configure `webpack.mix.js` to bundle up some javascript, and pass in a source map type to the `sourceMaps` method. The resulting build will not have source maps of the type specified. My build doesn't have javascript source maps at all, but I can't tell if that's the same issue.

```javascript
mix.js('resources/assets/main.js', 'public/assets')
   .sourceMaps(true, 'source-map');
```

title: Fails on Android
body:
Building on Android gives a `process` with no `getuid`. So it looks like this check is failing: https://github.com/isaacs/isexe/blob/master/mode.js#L26

This makes `npm i` impossible, since `python` is not considered an `exe`. But, `python` exists and otherwise works.

title: Update React component by dispatching action from non-react component
body:
Hi

I'm trying to update the cart-button on a project when the user adds an item to the cart.

I have build parts of the site in React.js - like the cart, the cart button etc. I'm dispatching an action that is supposed to update the card quantity from a non-react component like this:

```
import { dispatch } from 'redux';
import { updateCart } from '../../actions/cart_actions';
import configureStore from '../../store/configureStore'
var store = configureStore();
```

and then..

```
store.dispatch(updateCart(response));
```

The action **is dispatched** and **the state is updated**. The cart-button component is connected via. react-redux connect() function. But somehow it isn't updating the component with the new quantity.

When I dispatch an action from within my cart React component it works fine.

I might be missing something obvious. Any suggestions?

title: Cannot change the HMR port easily for multiple projects running simultaneously
body:
-   Laravel Mix Version: 4.1.4 (`npm list --depth=0`)
-   Node Version (`node -v`): 11.15.0
-   NPM Version (`npm -v`): 6.7.0
-   OS: macOS Catalina (10.15.2)

### Description:

I think that HMR is not working as it should. If you run the script `npm run hot` without providing a port argument, it will bind 8080 port. It is good for a single project. A lot of times I have 3-5 projects at once, so `laravel-mix` is not good enough for my work, yet. I'm currently using my own gulp+webpack combination, but I think it would be much better to use something popular like `laravel-mix`, so let's see what's my problem.

### Steps To Reproduce:

1. Start multiple laravel projects at once
2. The first project can be run with `php artisan serve` and `npm run hot`
3. The second project can be run with `php artisan serve`, now he detects, that the port 8000 is occupied, os it bind 8001 - so far so good
4. Now you want to run HMR in the second project, but `npm run hot` won't work, because it just "die" when the port 8080 is occupied
5. Ok then, run `npm run hot -- --port=8081`, hooray - it works!
6. Hold on! Webpack output is still served from port 8080! And here we go.
7. Open server URLs in the browser and now you see - both have the same assets!

Here is the screenshot:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3219895/72208491-8857f200-34a3-11ea-8989-9bb491a7ec36.png)

I have created 2 same laravel projects from scratch with a simple change in the app.scss - I have changed their body's background to see the effect:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3219895/72208505-b2a9af80-34a3-11ea-9db2-f3a2bbdb7db8.png)

When I look into the browser I see both projects having the same background:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3219895/72208527-f3a1c400-34a3-11ea-8255-c7c0b94d76ce.png)

The reason is simple - both projects' webpack are served from the same host.

The solution is also theoretically simple, just add this into the `webpack.mix.js` file:
```
mix.options({
        hmrOptions: {
            host: 'localhost',
            port: '8081'
        },
    })...
```

Now I re-run the script for `test2` project and it seems to be working well, even both projects now have different backgrounds!
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3219895/72208594-a96d1280-34a4-11ea-99ac-6bef63226d02.png)

### But this is not a good solution.

Why? Well, because you are changing a JS file, which is also in the project's repository and used by other coworkers. We can change a port for every project we create, but it's still a solution just for a single team. If you want to work on something your own/private or even for a different team, a random HMR port can be set in both teams for different projects, and it will cause a problem. Maybe it's not a common problem, but when this will occur, there will be no fix.

### What is a good solution then?

**Option 1:** make it possible to change HMR port in run command, for example: `npm run hot -- --port=8081 --hmr-port=8081`, since every developer is running this command separately, so there is no change for other developers.

**Option 2:** check for the occupied port, if it is occupied, then add +1 and so on, until there is a free port, which will add developers much better UX when running HMR. Artisan's serve is a good example.

Thank you if you will look at it and sorry for a long text, hope it is clear enough.

title: Duplicate actions with dispatching on componentWillReceiveProps and time-travel debugging
body:
In an application I work on, data is fetched in response to a store change, very similarly to how the `async` example works, and following the suggested pattern from issue #448. However, I've noticed with redux-devtools and time-travel debugging, there's an unfortunate consequence to this design. If you reverse actions and replay them, they can fire additional, unwanted actions that are appended to the end of the event stream. This leads to a messy event stream any time you replay actions that may cause a fetch async action.

This behavior can be reproduced by adding redux-devtools to the async example. You'll see if you revert and replay the actions, that the `fetchPostsIfNeeded` action will be called again [here](https://github.com/rackt/redux/blob/master/examples/async/containers/App.js#L22). This will append a new action to the end of the action stream.

Are actions fired from React lifecycle methods in response to store changes actually a bad pattern? If so, does anyone have any suggestions for alternatives that would not exhibit this behavior?

### Description:

title: Better emulate standard `require` for extensions that are not specified:
body:
Right now, if you do:

``` js
appendTransform(transformFn, '.foo');
```

And no one ever registers a handler for `.foo`, we throw an error if a `.foo` file is ever required.

Without `append-tranform` what [actually happens](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/19f700859b55b96c7ed9bdeb68482c6a9d84e1b2/lib/module.js#L365-L367) is that Node just tries to load it as a `.js` file.

This should be fixed.

Related: #5 

// @gotwarlost

title: Does not respect print width when chaining method call after property
Identifiers in JSX attributes not being uglified
body:
**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**

bug

**What is the current behavior?**

Uglify fails to process some identifiers.

I recently upgraded a React/Redux/TypeScript project from TypeScript 2.2 + Babel + Webpack 2.2 to TypeScript 2.3.2 + Webpack 2.5.1. This project makes heavy use of Immutable and i18next.

After the uglify process, my client.js bundle had exactly one reference to i18next_1.t and immutable_1.fromJS, which is odd because I use both all over the app. Both of these caused errors in the browser because i18next and immutable were undefined (the real ones had been uglified).

**If the current behavior is a bug, please provide the steps to reproduce.**

The two instances shared a few attributes:
- they were both referenced from within a JSX attribute
- they were both from a stateless React component

e.g. UglifyJSPlugin fails on this code (note that TypeScript changes the "t" in placeholder to be i18next_1.t)
```ts
import { t } from 'i18next';

export const TitleField = ({ input }: any) =>
    <input id="title" maxLength={ 32 } type="text" { ...input } placeholder={ t("TITLE_PLACEHOLDER") } autoFocus={ true }/>
;
```

However, it worked when I rewrote the component to have the function call outside of the JSX attribute:
```ts
import { t } from 'i18next';

export const TitleField = ({ input }: any) => {
    const placeholder = t("TITLE_PLACEHOLDER");
    return (
        <input id="title" maxLength={ 32 } type="text" { ...input } placeholder={ placeholder } autoFocus={ true }/>
    );
};
```

**What is the expected behavior?**

Identifier should be uglified

**If this is a feature request, what is motivation or use case for changing the behavior?**

n/a

**Please mention other relevant information such as the browser version, Node.js version, webpack version and Operating System.**

webpack v2.5.1
TypeScript v2.3.2
npm v4.0.5
node v6.9.4
Windows 7

title: asset_url configuration is not supported by mix()
body:
-   Laravel Mix Version: 4.0.14
-   Node Version (`node -v`): 11.9.0
-   NPM Version (`npm -v`): 6.8.0
-   OS: MacOS (High Sierra)

### Description:
Laravel Mix does not obey the `asset_url` available in Laravel that allows having dynamic asset URL - local or CDN. 

Here's the reference tweet by Taylor Otwell: https://twitter.com/taylorotwell/status/1062866359607062528?s=20

We are therefore unable to take advantage of Cache Bursting feature of Laravel Mix while hosting our assets on the CDN.

As of now loading assets urls via `mix()` method refers to the local version of the assets inside `public` directory. It'd be awesome if there is a way to make `mix()` make use of the `asset_url`. 

I'm not sure if it's a bug or a feature that's missing from Mix. But it'd be awesome to have it! Thanks.

title: !important appears twice if it follows a LESS mixin without whitespace
Cache option blocks configFile option
body:
Cache option is upper then configFile. Webpack rule **doesnt use** config file (tested with global eslint variable):
```
      {
        test: /\.(js|vue)$/,
        loader: "eslint-loader",
        include: /src/,
        enforce: "pre",
        options: {
          formatter: require("eslint-friendly-formatter"),
          cache: DEVELOPMENT,
          configFile:  path.resolve(__dirname, '.eslintrc.js'),
        }
      },
```
If cache option is lower then configFile is loaded but eslint **doesnt read rules** in `.eslintrc.js`
```
      {
        test: /\.(js|vue)$/,
        loader: "eslint-loader",
        include: /src/,
        enforce: "pre",
        options: {
          formatter: require("eslint-friendly-formatter"),
          configFile:  path.resolve(__dirname, '.eslintrc.js'),
          cache: DEVELOPMENT,
        }
      },
```

title: Fetching from Reddit API in advanced tutorial fails with CORS error in console on firefox (with strict enhanced tracking protection enabled)
body:
## What docs page needs to be fixed?

- **Section**: https://redux.js.org/advanced
- **Page**: https://redux.js.org/advanced/async-actions

## What is the problem?
When running Firefox (75.0) in "strict" (or certain configurations of custom) "Enhanced Tracking Protection" mode, calls toward the Reddit API fails with the following error in the console:

> Cross-Origin Request Blocked: The Same Origin Policy disallows reading the remote resource at https://www.reddit.com/r/reactjs.json. (Reason: CORS request did not succeed).

This was confusing, as I initially thought this was due to something I had done wrong in the tutorial.

After investigating some more, I started thinking it was an issue with the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header from the API as the exact same fetch code worked with https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/.

However the tutorial code _did_ work on chrome, which made the issue all the more confusing. I ended up finding someone else that had the same issue on [reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/redditdev/comments/di9y1t/reddit_api_calls_being_blocked_by_firefox_content/f3ua0ax/), which led me to test the "Standard" Enhanced Tracking Protection mode which made the tutorial code that I had written initially, work.

## What should be changed to fix the problem?
One solution could be to switch to some API in the example that is not considered a tracker by Firefox (or any other browser).

I also wanted to add this issue for posterity, so that if anyone else stumbles over the same issue, they won't have to waste as much time as I did with trying to find the root cause.
Comments: NOTHING THE maintainers can do

title: Delete `.(` warning in React Stateless Component
Have a way to send custom header without forcing lowercase
body: I know it was reported and closed in https://github.com/github/fetch/issues/249 . However, this way makes me impossible to call public API of third party servers that require uppercase header names (and we can't control those servers). If according to the spec the header should be case-insensitive I don't see why forcing the headers to be lower case matters then, we should be generally allowed to send headers in any case form.

title: Not reload with React.memo and defaultProps
Rendering connected component with undefined 'mergedProps' parameter throws TSLint error 2739
body:
I ran into an issue using React Redux together with TypeScript and TSLint.

I added the option parameter to the connect function for my component, having to put a nullified parameter for mergeProps in between.

```
export default connect<PropsFromState, PropsFromDispatch, OwnProps>(
    mapStateToProps,
    mapDispatchToProps,
    null,
    { forwardRef : true }
)(MyComponent);
```

**What is the current behavior?**

Wanting to render the component throws a TSLint error for me:

`<MyComponent ownProp ref={ref => this.comp = ref}/>`

> Type '{ ownProp: true; ref: (ref: Component<Pick<MyComponent, "ownProp" | "stateProp" | "dispatchProp"> & OwnProps, any, any>) => Component<...>; }' is missing the following properties from type 'Readonly<Pick<MyComponentProps, "ownProp" | "stateProp" | "dispatchProp"> & OwnProps>': stateProp, dispatchProp - ts(2739)

...basically asking for state and dispatch props where it shouldn't ask for them.

Tracing back the type definition of connect (via Visual Studio Code), it refers me to

```
<TStateProps = {}, TDispatchProps = {}, TOwnProps = {}, TMergedProps = {}, State = {}>(
	mapStateToProps: MapStateToPropsParam<TStateProps, TOwnProps, State>,
	mapDispatchToProps: MapDispatchToPropsParam<TDispatchProps, TOwnProps>,
	mergeProps: MergeProps<TStateProps, TDispatchProps, TOwnProps, TMergedProps>,
	options?: Options<State, TStateProps, TOwnProps, TMergedProps>
): InferableComponentEnhancerWithProps<TMergedProps, TOwnProps>;
```

**What is the expected behavior?**

The component should render without any issues, not asking for state and dispatch props.

The type definition of connect should actually refer to

```
<TStateProps = {}, TDispatchProps = {}, TOwnProps = {}, State = {}>(
	mapStateToProps: MapStateToPropsParam<TStateProps, TOwnProps, State>,
	mapDispatchToProps: MapDispatchToPropsNonObject<TDispatchProps, TOwnProps>,
	mergeProps: null | undefined,
	options: Options<State, TStateProps, TOwnProps>
): InferableComponentEnhancerWithProps<TStateProps & TDispatchProps, TOwnProps>;
```

**Which versions of React, ReactDOM/React Native, Redux, and React Redux are you using?  Which browser and OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of React Redux?**

React - 16.8.6
ReactDOM - 16.8.6
React Redux - 7.1.0
Redux - 4.0.1
TypeScript - 3.5.2
TSLint - 5.16,0
OS - Win 10 Enterprise x64
I haven't tested this with any previous version of React Redux.

title: Babel helper export is wrongly hoisted
body:
Is rollup able to code split inlined babel helpers?

I got an issue with this. This helper is exported at the top of the chunk with `exports({ e: _extends })`

```js
var _extends = Object.assign || function (target) { for (var i = 1; i < arguments.length; i++) { var source = arguments[i]; for (var key in source) { if (http://Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call (source, key)) { target[key] = source[key]; } } } return target; };
```

I guess it's inlined helper. Babel distributes babe-runtime with not minified helpers.

Moving `exports({})` to the bottom of the chunk should solve the problem.

 And I don't know how to reproduce this in small sandbox.

Using prime256v1
Private Key:'74864f3a6af4da4ad93d23d36ddf63f61ba4f42c33acb3ab78ce614010aa7ae2'
Public Key:'04d0769514776c9f0601435e79e0a1b5e59128a8cd0502f8700e4a2517eb0361b013bb80e18e385495ad1718b1b0ec5c7628e978889ec68a5edb13f2e9e17ce8ff'
Data Signed:"Hello" ==> '48656c6c6f'

The signature generation code using elliptic is as follows:

var key = ec.keyPair(privKey, 'hex');

title: [question] List.remove()
body:
Hey @lahmatiy ,

I'm trying to use `csstree` and `node-html-parser` to remove unused rules from a stylesheet.

What i have is to invoke `querySelector` on the parsed html structure and determine if there are any matches for any selector. If not, i can safely remove the selector form a `SelectorList`, and if the selector list becomes empty, i can remove the entire block. It seems like something that should be pretty easy but i'm finding the AST structure a bit too granular. For instance i need to split the selectors only on the `,` combinator but not have to reconstruct the rest of the selectors from the AST.

Ideally, given this:

```css
#list > #foo,
.x y {
  color: white;
}
```

i can get back `#list > #foo` and `.x y` and remove either one, or both, and also the entire block (if both). in my futile attempts, removing just `#list` from `#list, .abc`, for instance, still leaves me with the `, .abc` when i run `csstree.generate(ast)`.

any advice would be helpful, thanks!

title: Problem in recursive Component of SPA
body:
We can assume that: we have a SPA application consist of a `profile` page and a `followerList` page. The state tree is as shown in the following:

```
{
  profile: { name: xx, sex: xx },
  followerList: []
}
```

We can open a follower list page from a profile **page A**, and then open a profile **page B** from the follower list page. In my application, page A and page B share the same reducer `profile`.

Here is the problem: when page B rendered, the `profile` in state tree has been changed by B's info; when it returns back to page A, it is supposed to keep A's info, **but it has also been rendered by B's info**.

---

So far I've got two solutions:
1. Using a `profileList` to keep all profile pages have been opened. It means that I have to keep a list for every page which can be opened recursively.
2. Re-rendering the profile page when the page is returned. I don't think it's an elegant way.

How can I solve this problem?

title: change "combineReducers" to "joinReducers"
body:
**Do you want to request a _feature_ or report a _bug_?**  
bug
(If this is a _usage question_, please **do not post it here**‚Äîpost it on [Stack Overflow](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/redux) instead. If this is not a ‚Äúfeature‚Äù or a ‚Äúbug‚Äù, or the phrase ‚ÄúHow do I...?‚Äù applies, then it's probably a usage question.)

**What is the current behavior?**
"combineReducers" function name is being used.

**If the current behavior is a bug, please provide the steps to reproduce and if possible a minimal demo of the problem via https://jsfiddle.net or similar.**
"combineReducers" wording is confusing. "combine" means "put TWO together". But the so-called "combineReducers" is not limited to put TWO reducers together. It can be used to put two or more (that is, "multiple") reducers together. So it'd be more precise and easy to understand by re-naming it "joinReducers".

**What is the expected behavior?**
"joinReducers" function name

**Which versions of Redux, and which browser and OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of Redux?**
all versions.

Three ways  to reproduce:

Bug #1. Following the tutorial from https://rollupjs.org/guide/en/#tutorial create these files

```
import foo from './foo.js';

export default {

};

```

Bug #2. Repeat steps in bug #1 (rollup.config.js not necessary) but  run` rollup src/main.js -f esm` instead.



Bug #3. Follow all the standard steps in the tutorial all the way up to code splitting   part https://rollupjs.org/guide/en/#code-splitting where you enter rollup src/main.js src/main2.js -f esm -d dist

Bug #3 following tutorial up to code splitting when running  `rollup src/main.js src/main2.js -f esm -d dist` should output code splitting in ESM like this

```
<!doctype html>
<script type="module">
  import main2 from './dist/main2.js';
  main2();
</script>
```

var foo = 'hello world!';

title: Laravel-Mix 4.0.2 breaks /deep/ in Vue component styling
body:
<!--
    Before posting this issue, please perform the following steps, and confirm that the issue is still present.

1. Update Laravel Mix to the latest version. (`npm update laravel-mix` or `yarn upgrade laravel-mix --latest`)
2. Nuke your dependencies, and reinstall from scratch: `rm -rf node_modules && npm cache clear && npm install`.
3. Check your `package.json` file, and ensure that there are no old Laravel Elixir dependencies that might be interfering with Mix.
-->

-   Laravel Mix Version: 4.0.2 (`npm list --depth=0`)
-   Node Version (`node -v`): 11.3
-   NPM Version (`npm -v`): 6.5
-   OS: MacOS Mojave

### Description:
I have a Vue component where I need scoped styling to affect a child component.[ I use ```/deep/``` for this.](https://vue-loader.vuejs.org/guide/scoped-css.html#child-component-root-elements) This has always worked pre Laravel-Mix 4.
```html
<style lang="scss" scoped>
    /deep/ .some-styling {
    }
```

With Laravel-Mix 4, I get the following error on ```npm run dev```:
```
         }
     ^
      Expected selector.
    & /deep/ .some-foo-styling{
      ^
```
or 
```
    .some-other-styling {
^
      Expected selector.
/deep/.some-styling{
^

```
It seems clear that Mix no longer understands what ```/deep/``` is, so I tried replacing it with the thing that it's an alias for: ```>>>```

Mix now compiles without error, but sadly the generated CSS is wrong.
It should be:
```CSS
[data-v-507877ae] .some-styling {
}
```
but instead it generates:
```CSS
 > .some-styling[data-v-507877ae] {
}
```
which means that the class must now be a direct descendant, so my styling breaks.

title: Bug with `center left` value for background/background-position.
body:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/177485/18455139/d770ea2a-7950-11e6-808b-d47a5ad98d29.png)

`center left` should be valid as stated in the Note at [Spec](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-backgrounds-3/#background-position):

> Note that a pair of keywords can be reordered while a combination of keyword and length or percentage cannot. So ‚Äòcenter left‚Äô is valid while ‚Äò50% left‚Äô is not.

title: ShouldComponentUpdate bypassed when rendered from root
body:
### Description

There is a bug where shouldComponentUpdate is not being called. In our case it caused bugs to be discovered only in production mode, since the app was rendered on every small change in development mode. This is also a performance hit (which is important is development too).

### Expected behavior
shouldComponentUpdate should be raised before every render

### Actual behavior
shouldComponentUpdate is not being raised

### Environment
React Hot Loader version: 3.0.0-beta.X
1. `node -v`: v6.3.1
2. `npm -v`: 3.10.5

We have an app where on state changes we re-render from the top. On every render we would expect shouldComponentUpdate to be called, but it is not. Other lifecycle hooks we checked, are being raised as expected. We have reproduced it on the react-hot-boilerplate (see below).

1. Operating system: Windows 7
2. Browser and version: Chrome 54.0.2840.99 m (64-bit)

### Reproducible Demo
Next branch at:
https://github.com/omerts/react-hot-boilerplate

title: react/jsx-no-bind false positive?
Respect line breaks around directives
Could not find a declaration file for module 'axios/lib/adapters/http'
body:
**Describe the bug**
Importing the axios **HttpAdapter** in a unit test fails.

**To Reproduce**
Create a simple test file containing this at the start:
```
import axios from 'axios';
import httpAdapter from 'axios/lib/adapters/http';
import nock from 'nock';

axios.defaults.url = 'https://localhost';
axios.defaults.adapter = httpAdapter;
...
```
This produces the following error:
```
TS7016: Could not find a declaration file for module 'axios/lib/adapters/http'. 'C:/Users/<user>/<project>/node_modules/axios/lib/adapters/http.js' implicitly has an 'any' type.
  Try `npm install @types/axios` if it exists or add a new declaration (.d.ts) file containing `declare module 'axios';`
```

**Expected behavior**
I expected the import to work. I found a stackoverflow question related to this here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50954167/how-to-add-type-definitions-for-module-in-subdirectory

Following this I created `src/types/axios.d.ts` with the following contents:
```
declare module 'axios/lib/adapters/http' {
  import { Adapter } from 'axios';

  const HttpAdapter: Adapter;

  export default HttpAdapter;
}
```
and this seems to fix the issue but I consider it a workaround and it would be nice to have axios contain Typescript type definitions for all the types it defines.

**Environment:**
 - Axios Version [0.19.0]
 - OS: [OSX 10.14.5 (18F203)]
 - Browser [N/A]
 - Browser Version [N/A]
 - Additional Library Versions
  - Typescript [3.5.3]

**Additional context/Screenshots**
N/A

title: Null values being posted?
body:
Good day,

I have a strange issue that I've been trying to fix for about a week without any luck...

When I post to my API the int and datetime values are posted as null, which results in the API returning a 400 response.

Here's an example of the code:
```
        axios
            .post('http://localhost:5000/v1/resources/listings/', {
              category_id: 1,
              title: this.title,
              location: this.location,
              description: this.description,
              price: this.price,
              is_available: this.is_available,
              available_from: this.available_from,
              available_until: this.available_until
            })
            .then(response => {
              this.$router.push('/users/profile')
            })
            .catch(function(error) {
              // Show server response if the request doesn't return a HTTP 201 status code.
              self.$toast.open({
                message: error.response.data.error,
                type: 'is-danger',
                position: 'is-bottom'
              })
            })
```
In the above code I even hard coded the category_id but the response I get is still the same:
```
sqlalchemy.exc.OperationalError: (MySQLdb._exceptions.OperationalError) (1048, "Column 'category_id' cannot be null")
[SQL: INSERT INTO listings (category_id, title, location, description, price, is_available, available_from, available_until, created_at, modified_at) VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s)]
[parameters: (None, 'sdfew', 'efwef', 'wefweffew', '231', None, None, None, datetime.datetime(2019, 6, 14, 6, 50, 22, 465355), datetime.datetime(2019, 6, 14, 6, 50, 22, 465362))]
(Background on this error at: http://sqlalche.me/e/e3q8)
```

Any idea what's going wrong? It only happens on this endpoint...

I'm using a Flask API and Nuxt.js

title: Unsafe module export
body:
Elliptic declares the following in elliptic.js:

```js
var elliptic = exports;
```

This is causing problems when transpiling for browser use, as exports is undefined when called using webpack. Assigning properties on undefined throws an error.

This would be better suited to use a structure such as:
```js
const elliptic = {}
...
module.exports = elliptic
```
Comments: bug report sent to the wrong repo

title: relative urls without leading slash are not parsed properly
Axios fails on poylfilled URLSearchParams in IE11
body:
**Describe the bug**
I'm working on a project with IE11 support and Axios. As I also need some advanced URLSearchParams support, so I'm using [@ungap/url-search-params](https://github.com/ungap/url-search-params) to implement it.

https://github.com/axios/axios/blob/405fe690f93264d591b7a64d006314e2222c8727/lib/utils.js#L154-L156


**To Reproduce**
I couldn't try out the code in IE11 because runkit doesn't work in IE, but this should be able to reproduce the error.

```js
var axios = require("axios")
var URLSearchParamsPolyfill = require('@ungap/url-search-params')

window.URLSearchParams = URLSearchParamsPolyfill

axios.request({ url: 'https://example.com' });
```

**Expected behavior**
I expect to be able to use Axios with a URLSearchParams polyfill.

**Environment:**
 - Axios: 0.18.0
 - OS: Any OS
 - Browser: Internet Explorer
 - Browser Version: 11
 - Additional Library Versions: `@ungap/url-search-params`

**Additional context/Screenshots**
I'm not 100% sure where the place would be to fix this. Maybe there's also something to be don on the polyfill's side. I've filed the bug report here because axios supports IE11.
Comments: issue with pollyfill not axios

title: State not preserved during HMR when <script> is changed
body: I have tried the browserify and the webpack templates using vue-cli. In both cases, the state is preserved during HMR when I change the template portion, but not when I change the script portion of the `*.vue` file. To reproduce: - modify `src/components/Hello.vue` of the vue-cli created example: ``` html ``` - run the example with `npm run dev` - press 'inc' a few times to change the state - change `count -= 1` to `count -= 2` in the template part - after HMR, the counter value is preserved - change `count += 1` to `count += 2` in the script part - after HMR, the counter value is reset to 1 Tested on: Chrome & Firefox on macOS & Windows An example project using Vue.js 1.0 and the associated vueify+template I've created a few weeks ago preserves the state in both cases.

`process.env.VAR` being split into multiple lines breaks `rollup-plugin-replace`
body:
<!-- BUGGY OR UGLY? Please use this template.

Tip! Don't write this stuff manually.

1. Go to https://prettier.io/playground
2. Paste your code and set options
3. Press the "Report issue" button in the lower right

-->

**Prettier 1.7.4**
[Playground link](https://prettier.io/playground/#%7B%22content%22%3A%22function%20testing()%20%7B%5Cn%20%20const%20p%20%3D%20%7B%7D%3B%5Cn%20%20%2F%2F%20faking%20some%20tabs%20since%20I%20can't%20paste%20my%20real%20code%20in%5Cn%20%20if(true)%20%7B%5Cn%20%20%20%20if(false)%20%7B%5Cn%20%20%20%20%20%20return%20%60%24%7Bprocess.env.OPENID_URL%7D%2Fsomething%2Fsomething%2Fsomething%3F%24%7BObject.keys(p)%5Cn%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20.map(k%20%3D%3E%20%60%24%7BencodeURIComponent(k)%7D%3D%24%7BencodeURIComponent(p%5Bk%5D)%7D%60)%5Cn%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20.join(%5C%22%26%5C%22)%7D%60%3B%5Cn%20%20%20%20%7D%5Cn%20%20%7D%5Cn%7D%22%2C%22options%22%3A%7B%22ast%22%3Afalse%2C%22bracketSpacing%22%3Atrue%2C%22doc%22%3Afalse%2C%22jsxBracketSameLine%22%3Afalse%2C%22output2%22%3Afalse%2C%22parser%22%3A%22babylon%22%2C%22printWidth%22%3A80%2C%22semi%22%3Atrue%2C%22singleQuote%22%3Afalse%2C%22tabWidth%22%3A2%2C%22trailingComma%22%3A%22none%22%2C%22useTabs%22%3Afalse%7D%7D)
```sh
**Input:**
```jsx
function testing() {
  const p = {};
  // faking some tabs since I can't paste my real code in
  if(true) {
    if(false) {
      return `${process.env.OPENID_URL}/something/something/something?${Object.keys(p)
        .map(k => `${encodeURIComponent(k)}=${encodeURIComponent(p[k])}`)
        .join("&")}`;
    }
  }
}
```

**Output:**
```jsx
function testing() {
  const p = {};
  // faking some tabs since I can't paste my real code in
  if (true) {
    if (false) {
      return `${process.env
        .OPENID_URL}/something/something/something?${Object.keys(p)
        .map(k => `${encodeURIComponent(k)}=${encodeURIComponent(p[k])}`)
        .join("&")}`;
    }
  }
}
```
So as far as I could tell, there aren't any issues for this specific case in this or the [rollup plugin repo](https://github.com/rollup/rollup-plugin-replace). The standard way to inject process.env variables using rollup is to use the replace plugin. This rolls through your code and replaces strings that exactly match what you specify. This means if prettier turns `process.env.VAR` into `process.env.\nVAR`, then that environment variable is never replaced, and you get "process is not defined" or whatever other runtime error. I haven't run into this with the webpack.DefinePlugin, but I assume it works the same way, and would break as well.

So I'm not sure if this even needs to get fixed in this repo, or if maybe the plugins need to account for whitespace/be smarter in general about how they inject, but it's defintely an issue, and I figured this was the best place to start a discussion.

Thanks, let me know if there's any more info I can provide!

### Description

#### Summary

I am working through an issue with making an axios call to an invalid URL. A simple mistake I made in my URL is that when importing I was accidentally importing an object as the URL and so the request URL looked something like this "[object]/blog" which is an invalid URL. title: Connection failure when using node-spdy (HTTP/2) due to Transfer-Encoding: chunked header
body:
I've been using webpack-hot-middleware v2.1.0 with [node-spdy](https://github.com/indutny/node-spdy) to allow for more than 6 simultaneous connections (each tab/iframe consumes an extra connection thanks to HMR).

I recently tried to upgrade and found all the `/__webpack_hmr` connections would fail due to `net::ERR_SPDY_PROTOCOL_ERROR`. 

I narrowed down the failure to version 2.2.1 working and 2.3.0 causing the failure. Looking at the code diffs, it¬†looks to be the `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` header set in `middleware.js` is [illegal in HTTP/2](https://github.com/http2/http2-spec/commit/be23060f8a247d80bdbc947898d49c259c4d61d1). Commenting out the line fixes it (in both 2.3.0 and 2.12.0).

I haven't tested in non-HTTP2/SPDY land, but is this header needed?

title: Axios added duplicated content-length header when request already has a content-length header
body:
**Describe the bug**
Axios is a promise based HTTP client with browser and Node.js support. As an HTTP client, Axios wants to make sure the sent message contains a proper content-length header as well. So it includes a number type ‚ÄúContent-Length‚Äù header by default. This behavior can be observed in /node_modules/axios/lib/adapters/http.js, at line 45.
 
If request already has a lowercase "content-length" header, since they have different casing, the header included by Axios does not overwrite the one included by the request. So we‚Äôre sending two ‚Äúcontent-length‚Äù headers to the server (same values and different types). I believe this is not the expected behavior we want.

**Expected behavior**

Before set content-length header, Axios should check if there is a case insensitive "content-length" header.

IF THERE IS AN EXISTING CONTENT-LENGTH HEADER:
  COMPARE WITH CONTENT-LENGTH CALCULATED
  IF DISMATCH
    THROW ERROR
ELSE
  SET CONTENT-LENGTH HEADER IN AXIOS

**Environment:**
 - Axios Version 0.18.0
 - OS: Any
 - Node.js: Any

title: Error when working with immutable arrays with modified slice() method (`seamless-immutable`)
body:
## üêõ Bug Report

First of all, thanks for the great tool! I'm working on a large project that has previously used [seamless-immutable](https://github.com/rtfeldman/seamless-immutable) for managing the Redux state. I would like to use `immer` for new code but it seems that `immer` fails when it tries to shallow-copy an array with an overridden `slice()`. The overridden `slice()` produces a new readonly array which is not what `immer` expects.

I would suggest a harmless fix: use `Array.prototype.slice(base)` or `[...base]` instead of `base.slice()` in the `shallowCopy()` method. I think many would benefit from this kind of compatibility. Will be happy to make a PR.

## Link to repro

https://codesandbox.io/s/immer-sandbox-j7ke0

## To Reproduce

Steps to reproduce the behavior: see the error in the sandbox when used in combination with `seamless-immutable`.

## Observed behavior

An error: `"Cannot assign to read only property '0' of object '[object Array]'"`

## Expected behavior

Producing a result as designed.

## Environment

We only accept bug reports against the latest Immer version.

- **Immer version:**
- [x] I filed this report against the _latest_ version of Immer
- [x] Occurs with `setUseProxies(true)`
- [x] Occurs with `setUseProxies(false)` (ES5 only)

title: Strange behavior when header name matches HTTP request method
body:
####¬†Summary

Axios appears to treat headers names that correspond to lowercase HTTP methods incorrectly.

If the header name matches the current HTTP method, the header name is transformed to `0`:

```js
axios.post('http://localhost:8888/', null, {headers: {'post': 'test'}});
```

```
POST / HTTP/1.1
0: test
Accept: application/json, text/plain, */*
Get: test
User-Agent: axios/0.17.1
Host: localhost:8888
Connection: close
Content-Length: 0
```

If the header name matches a different HTTP method, it is removed:

```js
axios.post('http://localhost:8888/', null, {headers: {'get': 'test'}});
```

```
POST / HTTP/1.1
Accept: application/json, text/plain, */*
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
User-Agent: axios/0.17.1
Host: localhost:8888
Connection: close
Content-Length: 0
```

This only seems to happen when the header name is lowercase-a header named `Get` is handled correctly:

```
axios.post('http://localhost:8888/', null, {headers: {'Get': 'test'}});
```

```
POST / HTTP/1.1
Accept: application/json, text/plain, */*
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Get: test
User-Agent: axios/0.17.1
Host: localhost:8888
Connection: close
Content-Length: 0
```

I didn't see anything in the docs about special meaning for these header names when passed directly. `axios.defaults.headers` has keys that correspond to HTTP methods, but it doesn't seem to make sense to interpret the headers set directly in the same way.

####¬†Context

- axios version: 0.17.1
- Environment: node v8.9.1

title: Compiling Vue using modern mode causes an 'address in use' error when doing the second build.
body:
#### Issue description
The --modern flag in Vue allows you to build two projects - one with all of the necessary polyfills to allow older browsers to use your app, and a modern bundle which lacks then as well as various transpiling that modern browsers do not need.

This gives us the benefit of maintaining browser compatibility, but also slimming down the packages sometimes considerably for browsers that support certain features natively.

#### Technical info
* Webpack Bundle Analyzer version: 3.6.0
* Webpack version: 4.41.3
* Node.js version: 12.14.1
* npm version: 6.13.4
* OS: Windows 10

#### Debug info
How do you use this module? As CLI utility or as plugin?
Plugin

If CLI, what command was used? (e.g. `webpack-bundle-analyzer -O path/to/stats.json`)
npx vue-cli-service build --modern src/main.js

If plugin, what options were provided? (e.g. `new BundleAnalyzerPlugin({ analyzerMode: 'disabled', generateStatsFile: true })`)
No arguments.

What other Webpack plugins were used?
None

It would be nice to also attach webpack stats file.
It can be generated using these options:
```js
new BundleAnalyzerPlugin({
  analyzerMode: 'disabled',
  generateStatsFile: true,
  // Excludes module sources from stats file so there won't be any sensitive data
  statsOptions: { source: false }
})
```
`stats.json` will be created in Webpack bundle output directory.

It's worth noting that the modern build overwrote the stats.json created in the legacy build. I've captured both by quickly copying the stats file before it got overwritten. I do not suspect these will be relevant though, as it doesn't seem like an issue specific to my project.

[stats.json.txt](https://github.com/webpack-contrib/webpack-bundle-analyzer/files/4227657/stats.json.txt)
[stats-legacy.json.txt](https://github.com/webpack-contrib/webpack-bundle-analyzer/files/4227659/stats-legacy.json.txt)

title: Allow jsx-no-bind to ignore dom components
body:
In my point of view the `jsx-no-bind` rule is mostly for `PureComponent`, although there is consideration on GC performance, it should not be significant In many cases, we need to pass some arguments to an event handler, for example: ```js
  • this.onClickTag(name, selected)}>{text}
    • ``` This will trigger the `jsx-no-bind` rule, here we have 2 concerns: 1. If we are using a custom component in above code, we can pass `name` and `selected` to component's `props` and call `this.props.onClick(this.props.name, this.props.selected)` to prevent such function bindings, however we cannot do this with DOM components 2. DOM components are never `PureComponent`, so a large reason for `jsx-no-bind` rule will not be a benefit for DOM components For these reasons, I expect the `jsx-no-bind` can have a `ignoreDOMComponents` config to ignore function bindings on DOM components

title: Incorrect reduction of nested expression
body:
Reducing the expression `calc( (1em - calc( 10px + 1em)) / 2)` reduces incorrectly to `calc(1em - 5px)` (the correct one should be `-5px`).

A workaround is to add another operation, however this is far from ideal: `calc( (1em + (-1 * calc( 10px + 1em))) / 2)`.

I know the expressions look weird, but these actually are real-world examples from SASS-generated CSS (the inner `calc` expression is stored in a variable).

title: Bug: Scoped package dependency in mix extension is not recognized.
body:
<!-- 
    Before posting this issue, please perform the following steps, and confirm that the issue is still present.

1. Update Laravel Mix to the latest version. (`npm update laravel-mix` or `yarn upgrade laravel-mix --latest`)
2. Nuke your dependencies, and reinstall from scratch: `rm -rf node_modules && npm cache clear && npm install`.
3. Check your `package.json` file, and ensure that there are no old Laravel Elixir dependencies that might be interfering with Mix.
-->

- Laravel Mix Version: laravel-mix@2.1.11
- Node Version: v8.10.0
- NPM Version: 5.7.1
- OS: Fedora 27

### Description:
I'm trying to build a custom extension for laravel-mix which has few dependencies. These dependencies are scoped packages (i.e they begin with '@' symbol) e.g. `@fortawesome/fontawesome`.

Mix fails to recognize these scoped packages were already installed during the first run of the custom extension. So it tries to re-install them on consecutive run and gets stuck at this stage as I have set `this.requiresReload` to `true`.

> I have found the cause for this bug and will send a PR soon.

### Steps To Reproduce:
1. Create sample mix extension with scoped packages
```
let mix = require('laravel-mix');

class FontAwesome {
    dependencies () {
        this.requiresReload = true;

        return [ '@fortawesome/fontawesome' ];
    }
};

mix.extend('fontAwesome', new FontAwesome());
```
2. Add custom extension to the mix build chain in webpack.mix.js
```
require('<custom-extension-name>');

mix.js('resources/assets/js/app.js', 'public/js')
    .sass('resources/assets/sass/app.scss', 'public/css')
    .fontAwesome();
```
3. Run Mix using `npm run dev`

> It logs `Additional dependencies must be installed. This will only take a moment.` and installs the necessary dependencies (in this case `@fortawesome/fontawesome`)
> Then asks to re-run Mix. This is expected behaviour thus far.

4. But after re-run `npm run dev`

> It still cannot find the scoped package and tries to install it again which is unnecessary.
> It again asks to re-run Mix as I have set `this.requiresReload = true`. This creates a loop and never gets past this stage of loading dependencies.
